## Building a Chunked Drag-and-drop File Uploader in React

**Mental model:** A drop zone accepts files via drag-drop or a file input. Each file is split into chunks of a configurable size (`ceil(size / chunkSize)`); you upload them sequentially, advancing a per-file progress bar. Here uploads are simulated with timers, but the chunk loop is the real shape — it's what enables resumable/parallel uploads.

### Step 1 — Drop zone + file input
`dragover` must `preventDefault` to allow the drop.

```jsx
<div onDragOver={(e) => e.preventDefault()} onDrop={onDrop}>
  <input type="file" multiple onChange={(e) => add(e.target.files)} />
</div>
```

### Step 2 — Model files with chunk counts
```jsx
const add = (fileList) => {
  const next = [...fileList].map((f) => ({ id: uid(), name: f.name, size: f.size, sent: 0, total: Math.max(1, Math.ceil(f.size / chunkSize)) }));
  setFiles((cur) => [...cur, ...next]);
  next.forEach(upload);
};
```

### Step 3 — Upload chunks sequentially
```jsx
const upload = (file) => {
  const tick = () => setFiles((cur) => cur.map((f) => {
    if (f.id !== file.id || f.sent >= f.total) return f;
    return { ...f, sent: f.sent + 1 };
  }));
  const id = setInterval(() => { tick(); /* stop when done */ }, 200);
};
```

### Step 4 — Progress bar from sent/total
```jsx
<div style={{ width: `${(f.sent / f.total) * 100}%` }} />
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Empty/zero-byte file | `Math.max(1, …)` keeps at least one chunk. |
| Missing preventDefault | Drop won't fire without it on `dragover`. |
| Cleanup | Clear the per-file interval when it completes. |

**Interview tip:** Framing upload as a chunk loop (`ceil(size/chunkSize)`) is what the "configurable chunk size" ask is really probing — it's the foundation for retry/resume and parallelism, even though the demo just simulates the network.

