**Mental model:** A drop zone takes files via drag-drop or input. Each file is split into `ceil(size / chunkSize)` chunks uploaded sequentially, advancing a per-file progress bar. Chunk size is configurable. Uploads are simulated, but the chunk loop is the real shape.

### Step 1 — Drop zone (`@dragover.prevent`)
```vue
<div @dragover.prevent @drop.prevent="onDrop">
  <input type="file" multiple @change="add($event.target.files)" />
</div>
```

### Step 2 — Model files with chunk counts
```js
function add(list) {
  const size = chunkKB.value * 1024;
  [...list].forEach((f) => {
    const item = { id: uid(), name: f.name, size: f.size, sent: 0, total: Math.max(1, Math.ceil(f.size / size)) };
    files.value.push(item);
    upload(item);
  });
}
```

### Step 3 — Upload chunks
```js
function upload(item) {
  const id = setInterval(() => {
    if (item.sent >= item.total) { clearInterval(id); return; }
    item.sent++;
  }, 200);
}
```

### Step 4 — Progress
```vue
<div :style="{ width: (f.sent / f.total) * 100 + '%' }" />
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Zero-byte file | `Math.max(1, …)`. |
| Missing prevent | `@dragover.prevent` required. |
| Cleanup | Clear interval on completion. |

**Interview tip:** `@dragover.prevent` enables the drop, and the `ceil(size/chunkSize)` loop is the real answer to "configurable chunk size" — the basis for resume/retry/parallel uploads.

